When a country faces a crisis, there are certain legal justifications for emergency powers and for the restrictions on some human rights that these often entail. South Africa is no exception and citizens should accept the loss of some freedoms for the greater good. However, there is a worry that a disaster situation, such as we currently face with the coronavirus, can be repeatedly extended and that the temporary structures set up to deal with the emergency may continue to exercise their vast power over us. Those are the concerns expressed to President Cyril Ramaphosa by two advocates, who believe...